post_text:
There is still time to complete your Census information if you have not yet. The CAN Council is putting on a Census BBQ tomorrow September 10th from 11am-2pm at the COPOCO Credit Union on Wilder! Check out the flyer below for more info.

How the Census Benefits You and Your Community
--Federal funds, grants and support to states, counties and communities are based on population totals and breakdowns by sex, age, race and other factors. Your community benefits the most when the census counts everyone. When you respond to the census, you help your community gets its fair share of the more than $675 billion per year in federal funds spent on schools, hospitals, roads, public works and other vital programs.

--Businesses use census data to decide where to build factories, offices and stores, and this creates jobs. Developers use the census to build new homes and revitalize old neighborhoods. Local governments use the census for public safety and emergency preparedness. Residents use the census to support community initiatives involving legislation, quality-of-life and consumer advocacy.

Just another day at BACHS: Lots of things look different this year...masks; hand sanitizer; checking in students using our new fancy tent each morning and after lunch - taking temps, completing questionnaires; social distancing; lots of cleaning; and...laundry at the end of the day...and repeat!!

post_text: Can't wait to see all of our in-seat Bulldogs tomorrow morning!! School starts at 8am with breakfast around 730-755am. Don't forget if you catch the metro to the main station, look for the yellow Bay-Arenac ISD bus that will bring you straight to school from the main station. Masks are required on the bus. All other belongings will be stored in your locker before heading to first hour. Locker numbers and combo's will be on your schedule that Katie and Corbett will be handing out as you come in the door. Locks are provided! Masks will also be provided during the morning check in. #bachsrocks #riseup #welcomeback

post_text:
BACHS is starting in-person learning on August 24th. We are offering two options for our students or those that enroll. In person learning will follow a full school calendar starting on August 24th. Protocols will be in place to promote safety of students and staff. In-Person will be a blended learning model using an online platform with teacher instruction. Online Learning will consist of 100% virtual with communication (email, phone, text) with the mentor teacher once a week. For more information on our plan offerings click here: https://bachs.us/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=652107&id=0

If you are looking for 9-12 grade in-person instruction this year click on this link for the Enrollment Application: https://bachs.us/apps/forms2/?f=10797

post_text:
It is with heavy hearts that we post this today. We lost one of our Bulldog Family! He was the guy always behind the camera... behind the scenes to make sure our events were captured on video and in photos. He didn't love the spotlight but when he smiled, he certainly lit up a room! His time was cut way too short and he will be missed by many. Our thoughts are with his family and his dear friends. https://www.skorupskifamilyfunerals.com/obituaries/Brian-Richard-Farrell/

Current and past students: If you are in need of support or someone to talk to please reach out to Katie or your Top Dog Teacher. If the support you need is more than just a conversation, please visit: Baisdcounseling.com. There is teletherapy available with two mental health counselors. Additional resources include the Children's Grief Center (989-495-9335); Text help to 741741; and the Suicide Prevention Hotline at 1-800-273-8225.

BACHS Superintendent Erin Sullivan is pleased to announce her replacement!

Earlier this year, Erin shared her intent to retire at the end of this school year. Chanda Swartz, current Special Education teacher at BACHS, has been chosen to succeed Erin. Erin told the Board of Directors she is confident Chanda is the best candidate for the position. She also shared she is excited about the ideas Chanda spoke about during her interview. Erin is certain Chanda will maintain and even enhance the momentum of success for all students!

Congratulations Chanda!! We’re all very excited for you!!

If you or someone you know is struggling with mental health right now, there is a new "WarmLine" number that you can call to talk to someone. The warmline will operate seven days a week from 10 a.m. to 2 a.m. at 888-PEER-753 (888-733-7753). It is intended to serve individuals living with persistent mental health challenges including anxiety, depression and trauma. Individuals in crisis, including those considering suicide, are urged to contact the Disaster Distress Helpline 24/7 at 800-985-5990 or the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline 24/7 at 800-273-8255.

https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98158-525635--,00.html

SNAP Outreach at Food Bank Council of Michigan
March 28 at 8:55 PM ·

To help Michiganders receive unemployment benefits as a result of COVID-19, the Michigan Unemployment Insurance Agency (UIA) has developed a schedule for workers to file for benefits based on the first letter of their last name. The agency continues to see a historical increase in working families seeking emergency financial relief and this new schedule will improve functionally, accessibility and help alleviate bottlenecks in both the online system - Michigan.gov/UIA - and over the phone at 866-500-0017.

The day or time of day in which a claim is filed will not impact whether a worker receives benefits or their benefit amount. Additionally, claims will be back-dated to reflect the date in which a claimant was laid-off or let go from their job due to COVID-19. The eligibility window to apply has also been increased from 14 to 28 days from the date of their work stoppage.

For more information: https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus/0,9753,7-406-98163-523365--,00.html

Thank you!
